      "value": "Del Mar Union Elementary is a small elementary (K-6) district on the North Coast of San Diego County. About 406 of its students have an IEP, and 78 of them \u2014 roughly 19% \u2014 have an autism (ASD) eligibility. Around 37% of those autistic students spend most of the school day in a general-education classroom."
    },
    "what_this_means_for_parents": {
      "ai_disclaimer": "This summary was written by an AI model from the data points in this profile. The underlying numbers come from public California government sources, but the narrative is AI-written and may contain inaccuracies. Verify specific claims directly with the school district before making decisions.",
      "ai_generated": true,
      "ai_generated_at": "2026-05-17T18:35:20Z",
      "ai_model": "claude-opus (via Claude Code session)",
      "based_on_sources": [
        "cde_spedps",
        "ca_dashboard"
      ],
      "value": "About 37% of autistic students here are in a general-education classroom for most of the day, and none are reported in a fully separate setting, so many spend part of the day in specialized settings. Among all students with disabilities, a broader group than autism alone, 71% are in general-education classrooms most of the day. On 2024-25 state tests, students overall scored well above standard \u2014 82 points above in English and 78 above in math \u2014 and students with disabilities also scored above standard in English, by 7 points, and just below in math, by 2 points. Students with disabilities were chronically absent at about 13% (compared with 7% for all students) and suspended at about 2%."
    }
  },
